The reason why is simply sociological shorthand. We started calling them big calories (calories with a capital C, ie Calories) and small calories for kg and g respectively. So, yes. text:
To clear up the kcal thing:
calorie with a lower case "c" is different from Calorie with an uppercase "C"

Big C is what we all use and know and it's used in food labels in almost every countries
1 Calorie = 1,000 calories
1,000 calories = 1 kcal
Therefore: 1 kcal = 1 Calorie

It would humanly physically impossible to burn 31,000 Calories with big "C"  (for those that thought that's what kcal meant)
The World Record for most burned in a day is 19,000 Calories

text:
Ringfit's easy! Even on the 30 difficulty!

The hard part is turning it into a routine. I think the best way to approach ringfit if you want to play it on 30 from the get go is to limit yourself for 10 in-game minutes max then keep increasing once you've developed enough tolerance to DOMs.

If you're sore, stop. Excercising while sore does more damage to your muscle tissues than good. If you wanna keep excercising, focus on different muscles and cycle through them once you've devveloped a tolerance.

I'm actually at a point where I can play ringfit for an hour or more. But the box says that ringfit adventures is supposed to be a 30 minute excercise program that should span 3 months so I'm keeping it that way. You could always add your own routine at the end since you're already warmed up, sweaty, and active. Pushups, crunches, and the like I think are great after-game excercises.

If you don't own a switch, I think getting a switch just for ringfit adventures is worth it.
